What you’re seeing there are xterm escape sequences to set the color of the text; `<ESC>[0m` resets the color. Apparently, whatever terminal Git Bash uses under Windows doesn’t use xterm’s escape sequence, but instead other ones.

In theory, there’s a really nice mechanism (terminfo) to let applications discover what escape sequences the terminal they’re running in uses. However, git-imerge doesn’t use it, but instead prints [hard-coded escape sequences](https://github.com/mhagger/git-imerge/blob/0bb758981534f82b3a428d43e7c46e095d921345/git-imerge#L233).

@mhagger I’m no python expert. In bash, I would write something like `BLACK = $(tput setaf 0)` (“set ascii foreground 0”) – would that be difficult to do in python?

@mhagger yes, branch `issue-62` works fine for me with `Python 2.7.5` :smiley: 

Let me know if you need me to test anything else.

Thanks for your comprehensive and informative answer!

> I haven't seen this problem myself (but haven't used imerge recently); I wonder if `git commit --allow-empty` would work as well.

@jmah: Indeed, that is the workaround that I use. In fact, I don't think that `--allow-empty` is needed, because merge commits are always allowed to be empty.

I just implemented #98, which I think should fix this problem for once and for all. It would be great if people who have experienced this problem would test it.

Thanks for pinging me; otherwise it can take a while for me to notice such notifications.

@greened: Thanks for the contribution! It was not my intention to change the authorship of commits during rebase-with-history simplification; that was an oversight.

I'd prefer to put in your fix *without* the new command-line option. Would you mind creating a new PR with only the fix?

> These operations can both conflict, so they both can benefit from using the incremental merge approach.

@mhagger I feel that this point is not clear enough in the documentation (README, and possibly help message of those subcommands). Without this clarification, it feels like the two commands introduced here do not really belong with `git-imerge`, and make the tool seemingly break the Unix philosophy.

Do you think you could add that clarification in the relevant places? Otherwise, if you'd give me some pointers about which files to edit and how, I could take a stab at doing this.
